Adelani Adepegba, Abuja Following the approval of the Federal Government for the enrolment of retired police officers on the National Health Insurance Scheme, the Inspector-General of Police, Mohammed Adamu, has directed the nationwide registration and capturing of all ex-police officers with effect from September 7 -23, 2020. With this development, all retired police officers, irrespective of their rank on retirement, along with a spouse, will have full access to all NHIS services and benefits covered by the Police Health Maintenance Organisation Code-073. A statement by the force spokesman, DCP Frank Mba, on Thursday, said the exercise, which would be in three batches, will take place at the various police area commands in the country. It asked all retired police officers to visit any area command closest to them with their National Identity Number, letter of retirement and identity card. The statement read, “The nationwide registration/capturing exercise is scheduled as follows; September 7-9: Jigawa, Kaduna, Kano, Katsina, Kebbi, Sokoto, and Zamfara; Adamawa, Bauchi, Borno, Gombe, Taraba, and Yobe. “September14- 16: Ekiti, Lagos, Ogun, Ondo, Osun, Oyo; Benue, Kogi, Kwara, Niger, and Plateau. “September 21-23; Cross River, Akwa Ibom, Edo, Delta, Rivers and Bayelsa; Abia, Anambra, Ebonyi, Enugu, Imo.” The IGP observed that the development would help in addressing the quest for affordable healthcare services for police retirees and enjoined them to take optimum advantage of the scheme.